---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const siteUrl = Astro.site?.href ?? 'https://paddletoday.com/';
const websiteId = new URL('/#website', siteUrl).href;
const organizationId = new URL('/#organization', siteUrl).href;
const aboutUrl = new URL('/about/', siteUrl).href;
const aboutStructuredData = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'AboutPage',
  '@id': `${aboutUrl}#about-page`,
  name: 'About Paddle Today',
  description:
    'Learn how Paddle Today ranks paddling routes, checks river and weather data, and explains when a recommendation needs extra caution.',
  url: aboutUrl,
  isPartOf: {
    '@id': websiteId,
  },
  about: {
    '@id': organizationId,
  },
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Paddle Today | How Route Scores Work"
  description="Learn how Paddle Today ranks paddling routes, checks river and weather data, and explains when a recommendation needs extra caution."
  structuredData={aboutStructuredData}
>
  <section class="info-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">About Paddle Today</p>
    <h1>How Paddle Today makes the call</h1>
    <p class="muted">
      Paddle Today helps you figure out where to paddle today. It pulls together river level, recent trend, weather, route notes, and data freshness so you can start with the best-looking options instead of bouncing between sources.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      The score isn't a safety guarantee. It's a shortcut to help you decide what's worth a closer look before you drive.
    </p>
    <div class="info-hero__actions">
      <a class="river-link river-link--inline" href="/">See today's board</a>
      <a class="river-link river-link--inline river-link--ghost" href="/request-river/">Request a route</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="info-grid" aria-label="How to read Paddle Today scores">
    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Score</p>
      <h2>What the rating means</h2>
      <ul class="compact-list">
        <li><strong>Strong:</strong> level, trend, weather, and data support all line up well.</li>
        <li><strong>Good:</strong> a solid option, but one thing may be worth a second look.</li>
        <li><strong>Fair:</strong> maybe worth it for the right paddler, but there's a real caution to keep in mind.</li>
        <li><strong>No-go:</strong> probably not worth it for most paddlers today.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Inputs</p>
      <h2>Where the data comes from</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        The board uses USGS gauge readings where available, weather forecasts, route distance and access notes, and published or curated river-level guidance. Each route page links back to the key sources so you can double-check before you launch.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Support</p>
      <h2>What support level means</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        A well-supported route has a fresh, relevant gauge and clearer threshold guidance. Some uncertainty usually means the gauge is indirect, the guidance is thinner, or the latest read needs a closer source check.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="info-grid" aria-label="What to verify before paddling">
    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Weather</p>
      <h2>Why weather can drag a score down</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        Cold air, wind, storms, and incoming rain can turn a technically runnable route into a poor pick for a lot of paddlers. When that happens, the route may still be possible, but it gets ranked lower on purpose.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Limits</p>
      <h2>What can still change fast</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        Rain, debris, ice, access closures, parking rules, and local hazards can change faster than the board refreshes. Treat the recommendation as a first pass, then check the source links and what you see on the ground.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Coverage</p>
      <h2>Why some routes aren't here yet</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        Paddle Today works best when there's enough source data to make a useful call. If you can share a put-in, take-out, and relevant USGS gauge, that route is much easier to add.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="info-panel">
    <p class="eyebrow">Common sources</p>
    <h2>The site leans on public data and route-specific references.</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Not every route uses every source. The route page is still the best place to check a specific recommendation, but these are the sources Paddle Today uses most often:
    </p>
    <ul class="compact-list">
      <li><strong>USGS Water Data:</strong> live gauge readings, recent trend, and gauge freshness.</li>
      <li><strong>National Weather Service:</strong> hourly forecast, wind, temperature, storm risk, and nearby station observations.</li>
      <li><strong>NOAA MRMS QPE:</strong> recent radar-estimated rainfall around the route.</li>
      <li><strong>State DNR pages:</strong> Minnesota, Wisconsin, and Iowa route maps, river-level notes, public-water-access records, and water-trail guidance.</li>
      <li><strong>Local city and county pages:</strong> put-in/take-out access, park hours, parking rules, launch details, and closure context.</li>
      <li><strong>Trip reports and paddling references:</strong> sources such as MilesPaddled when official river-level thresholds are incomplete.</li>
      <li><strong>Map sources:</strong> OpenStreetMap, OpenFreeMap, and MapLibre for map display and access context.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="info-panel">
    <p class="eyebrow">How to use it</p>
    <h2>Start with the board, then double-check the route.</h2>
    <ul class="compact-list">
      <li>Use the top picks to find the best-looking options first.</li>
      <li>Set a city or ZIP if drive time matters.</li>
      <li>Open the route page and check the gauge, weather, access notes, and source links.</li>
      <li>Check conditions again before you drive, especially after rain or during shoulder season.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
